\chapter{Original Problem 1: The Golden Ratio GP}

\section*{Design Notes}

\subsection*{Archetype Constellation}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \archetype{6} Linearization / Simplification
    \item \archetype{11} Uniqueness / Existence Conditions
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Design Intent}
To create a bidirectional problem where:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The recursion constraint (Existence) forces a specific value of $r$
    \item The log transformation (Linearization) reveals the AP structure
    \item Neither archetype alone suffices—both are needed for complete solution
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{Convergence Structure}
The recursion $ar^{n+1} = ar^n + ar^{n-1}$ simplifies to $r^2 = r + 1$, yielding $r = \phi$. Taking logs then shows:
\[
\log(ar^n) = \log a + n \log r = \log a + n \log \phi
\]
which is an AP with common difference $\log \phi$.

The convergence point is the recognition that the Fibonacci recursion structure \textit{determines} the golden ratio, and the golden ratio \textit{guarantees} the AP structure in log-space.

\subsection*{Unidirectional Traps}

\textbf{Trap 1 (Existence without Linearization):}
Students solve $r^2 - r - 1 = 0$ correctly, get $r = \phi$, but then struggle with part (b) because they haven't made the log-space connection explicit.

\textbf{Trap 2 (Linearization without Existence):}
Students take logs immediately, get $\log(ar^n)$, recognize it's AP-like, but can't determine what $r$ must be without the recursion constraint.

\subsection*{Difficulty Calibration}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Target level:} JEE Advanced
    \item \textbf{Expected solving time:} 15-20 minutes
    \item \textbf{Key insight:} Recognizing that Fibonacci recursion ↔ golden ratio ↔ AP in log-space
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Pedagogical Value}
This problem teaches:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Connection between different mathematical structures (GP, Fibonacci, AP, $\phi$)
    \item Bidirectional reasoning (constraint determines ratio; ratio guarantees structure)
    \item Domain translation (multiplicative → additive via logarithms)
\end{enumerate}
