10.1 Case Study 1: The Polygon Problem (Bidirectional)
Problem: Interior angles of polygon in AP, smallest = 120°, common difference = 5°. Find number of sides.

Archetype Analysis:

Primary: #9 (Domain Constraints)
Secondary: #1 (Invariance)
Structure: Bidirectional (2 archetypes)
Difficulty: Moderate (JEE Advanced level)
Multidirectional Structure:

       Invariance
     (Algebraic sum)
            |
            ↓
     [SOLUTION: n=9]
            ↑
            |
    Domain Constraints
   (Geometric filtering)
Direction 1 (Invariance):

Sum of angles = (n-2)×180° (fixed)
Sum of AP = (n/2)[2(120) + (n-1)(5)]
Equate: generates candidates n ∈ {9, 16}
Direction 2 (Domain Constraints):

All angles must be < 180°
For n=16: max angle = 195° > 180° ✗
For n=9: max angle = 160° < 180° ✓
Convergence: Only n=9 satisfies both algebraic and geometric constraints.

Takeaway: "Algebra generates candidates; Geometry selects the winner."

Pedagogical Value:

Teaches bidirectional thinking
Shows constraint intersection
Memorable principle
Transfers to physics (time > 0), probability (p ∈ [0,1]), etc.
10.2 Case Study 2: IMO 1988 Problem 6 (Multidirectional)
Problem: If (ab+1) | (a²+b²), prove (a²+b²)/(ab+1) is a perfect square.

Archetype Analysis:

Primary: #11 (Existence/Uniqueness)
Secondary: #16 (Reverse Engineering)
Tertiary: #18 (Infinite Descent)
Structure: Multidirectional (3 archetypes)
Difficulty: Extreme (IMO P6)
Multidirectional Structure:

         Existence
       (k ∈ ℕ forced)
              |
              ↓
 Reverse Eng → [SOLUTION: k=n²] ← Infinite Descent
 (Vieta jump)                     (Terminates at k=1)
Direction 1 (Existence):

Divisibility forces k = (a²+b²)/(ab+1) ∈ ℕ
Rewrite: a² - kab + b² = k
This is a constraint on possible k values
Direction 2 (Reverse Engineering):

Treat as quadratic in a: a² - (kb)a + (b²-k) = 0
Vieta: if a is root, exists a' = kb-a (also valid)
Transformation (a,b) → (a',b) preserves k
Direction 3 (Infinite Descent):

Choose minimal pair (a,b)
If a' < a, contradicts minimality
Eventually a = b
Base case: (1,1) gives k = 1 = 1²
Convergence: All three directions prove k must be perfect square:

Existence says k is constrained integer
Reverse Engineering generates sequence preserving k
Descent shows sequence terminates at k = 1²
Therefore k must always be perfect square ✓
Why Multidirectional is Essential:

Existence alone: Can't prove k is perfect square
Reverse Engineering alone: Can't prove k must have this property
Descent alone: Can't prove base case yields squares
All three together: Complete, elegant proof
Takeaway: "When direct construction fails, build a descent. Infinite descent transforms existence questions into minimality arguments."

Pedagogical Value:

